Note:
CMake Translation Round-Trip Probe

End-to-end proof that the CMake translation pipeline is REAL, not a skeleton:

    CMakeLists.txt source
      -> cmake_lexer    (tokenize: commands, ${VAR}, $<genexpr>, strings,
                         control-flow keywords, parens)
      -> cmake_parser   (build CMake command/control-flow AST)
      -> cmake_to_hir   (lower commands to HIR call expressions, set() to HIR
                         let statements, if/foreach to HIR control flow,
                         function() to HIR process definitions)
      -> hir_to_cmake   (emit the HIR tree back to CMake script text)

The probe feeds a representative CMakeLists.txt containing:
  - cmake_minimum_required(VERSION 3.20)
  - project(MyApp)
  - set(SRC_FILES main.c util.c)        (-> HIR let statement)
  - add_executable(myapp ${SRC_FILES})  (-> HIR call expression)
  - add_library(mylib STATIC lib.c)     (-> HIR call expression)
  - target_link_libraries(myapp mylib)  (-> HIR call expression)
  - an if(WIN32) ... endif() guard      (-> HIR if statement)
  - a foreach(f ${SRC_FILES}) ... endforeach() loop (-> HIR for statement)
  - a function(my_func) ... endfunction() (-> HIR process definition)

It then:

  1. Drives the source through lexer -> parser -> to_hir and asserts the HIR
     root is the program node carrying a single block child.
  2. Walks the first-stage HIR statements and asserts the lowered command
     names, the set() variable name, the if condition text, the foreach
     iterator name, and the function name survived.
  3. Emits the HIR back to CMake text and asserts the text is non-empty.
  4. Re-parses the emitted CMake text back into HIR (the SECOND emission) and
     asserts the two HIR statement streams are STRUCTURALLY EQUAL via a
     recursive comparator: same statement count, same node kind at each
     position, same command name / variable name / nesting at each position,
     compared by content rather than byte identity. Structural equality is the
     correct semantic-equivalence check: the backend canonicalises whitespace
     and indentation so the byte stream differs while the meaning is identical.

Exit code: number of failed assertions (0 == all passed). No exit_with_code.
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/cmake/cmake_lexer.runa" as CMakeLexer
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/cmake/cmake_parser.runa" as CMakeParser
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/cmake/cmake_to_hir.runa" as CMakeFrontend
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/cmake/hir_to_cmake.runa" as CMakeBackend
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir.runa" as HIR
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "tests/test_utils.runa" as TestUtils

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Pipeline driver: CMake source -> HIR program node
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The CMake pipeline has no single source-to-HIR convenience, so the probe owns
the chain explicitly: create_lexer produces the byte-positioned lexer,
create_parser primes the parser by consuming the first token, parse builds the
command/control-flow AST, and translate_cmake_to_hir lowers the AST to an HIR
program node holding a single block of statements. Returning the program
pointer (or 0 on any stage failure) lets the caller assert on one value.
@End Reasoning
Process called "cmake_source_to_hir" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from CMakeLexer with source
    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let parser be proc create_parser from CMakeParser with lexer
    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let ast be proc parse from CMakeParser with parser
    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let hir_program be proc translate_cmake_to_hir from CMakeFrontend with ast
    Return hir_program
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HIR accessors (mirror the backend's read contract)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
translate_cmake_to_hir returns an HIR program node whose children list lives at
offset 24 with the count at offset 32. The CMake frontend attaches exactly one
block child holding all top-level statements. This helper unwraps the program
to that statement-bearing block so every other accessor operates on the block.
@End Reasoning
Process called "program_block" takes program as Integer returns Integer:
    If program is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with program, 24
    If children is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc get from List with children, 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
A block node carries its statement list at offset 24 and the count at offset
32. This returns the statement count so assertions and the comparator know how
many statements to walk.
@End Reasoning
Process called "block_count" takes block as Integer returns Integer:
    If block is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 32
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns statement i of a block as a raw node pointer so callers can read its
node kind (offset 0) and per-kind fields.
@End Reasoning
Process called "block_stmt_at" takes block as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    If block is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let statements be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 24
    If statements is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc get from List with statements, index
End Process

@Reasoning:
Every HIR node stamps its kind constant at offset 0. This returns the kind so
the comparator and assertions can dispatch on call vs let vs if vs for vs
process-definition statements.
@End Reasoning
Process called "node_kind" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
A lowered CMake command is an HIR call expression whose callee identifier sits
at offset 8 and the identifier's name string at offset 40. This returns the
command-name string pointer so the probe can assert which command each
statement represents.
@End Reasoning
Process called "call_name" takes call as Integer returns Integer:
    If call is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let kind be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with call, 0
    If kind is not equal to HIR_CALL_EXPRESSION from HIR:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let callee be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with call, 8
    If callee is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with callee, 40
End Process

@Reasoning:
A call expression stores its argument list at offset 16 and the count at offset
24. This returns the argument count so the comparator can verify per-call arity.
@End Reasoning
Process called "call_argc" takes call as Integer returns Integer:
    If call is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with call, 24
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns argument i of a call (argument list at offset 16) as a raw node so the
content comparator can read its string payload.
@End Reasoning
Process called "call_arg_at" takes call as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    If call is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let args be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with call, 16
    If args is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc get from List with args, index
End Process

@Reasoning:
Argument nodes are HIR literals (string payload at offset 40) or identifiers
(name at offset 40); both store the comparable string at offset 40. This
returns that string pointer for content comparison, mirroring the backend
which reads offset 40 for both literal values and identifier names.
@End Reasoning
Process called "arg_string" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 40
End Process

@Reasoning:
A lowered set() command is an HIR let statement: the variable name string is at
offset 8. This returns that name for the variable-survival assertion.
@End Reasoning
Process called "let_var_name" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let kind be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 0
    If kind is not equal to HIR_LET_STATEMENT from HIR:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 8
End Process

@Reasoning:
A lowered if() command is an HIR if statement: the condition expression is at
offset 8. The CMake frontend lowers the whole condition token sequence to a
single verbatim string literal whose text is at offset 40. This digs to that
condition text for the survival assertion.
@End Reasoning
Process called "if_condition_text" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let kind be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 0
    If kind is not equal to HIR_IF_STATEMENT from HIR:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let condition be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 8
    If condition is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with condition, 40
End Process

@Reasoning:
A lowered foreach() command is an HIR for statement: the iterator variable is an
identifier node at offset 8 whose name string is at offset 40. This returns the
iterator name for the survival assertion.
@End Reasoning
Process called "for_iterator_name" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let kind be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 0
    If kind is not equal to HIR_FOR_STATEMENT from HIR:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let iterator be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 8
    If iterator is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with iterator, 40
End Process

@Reasoning:
A lowered function() command is an HIR process definition: the process name
string is at offset 8. This returns the function name for the survival
assertion.
@End Reasoning
Process called "process_name" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let kind be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 0
    If kind is not equal to HIR_PROCESS_DEFINITION from HIR:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 8
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Structural equality of two CMake HIR statement streams
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Two CMake scripts are semantically equal when their lowered HIR statement
streams match position-for-position: same statement count, same node kind at
each position, and -- for the kinds the round trip must preserve -- the same
identifying payload (command name + argument string payloads for calls, the
variable name for let statements, the condition text for ifs, the iterator name
for fors, the process name for process definitions). This is whitespace- and
indentation-insensitive, so it proves round-trip fidelity without being fooled
by the backend's canonical re-rendering.
@End Reasoning
Process called "hir_blocks_equal" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let count_a be proc block_count with a
    Let count_b be proc block_count with b
    If count_a is not equal to count_b:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count_a:
        Let stmt_a be proc block_stmt_at with a, i
        Let stmt_b be proc block_stmt_at with b, i

        Let kind_a be proc node_kind with stmt_a
        Let kind_b be proc node_kind with stmt_b
        If kind_a is not equal to kind_b:
            Return 0
        End If

        Note: Call expressions: compare command name, arity, and every
        Note: argument string payload by content.
        If kind_a is equal to HIR_CALL_EXPRESSION from HIR:
            Let name_a be proc call_name with stmt_a
            Let name_b be proc call_name with stmt_b
            Let names_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with name_a, name_b
            If names_match is not equal to 1:
                Return 0
            End If

            Let argc_a be proc call_argc with stmt_a
            Let argc_b be proc call_argc with stmt_b
            If argc_a is not equal to argc_b:
                Return 0
            End If

            Let j be 0
            While j is less than argc_a:
                Let arg_a be proc call_arg_at with stmt_a, j
                Let arg_b be proc call_arg_at with stmt_b, j
                Let str_a be proc arg_string with arg_a
                Let str_b be proc arg_string with arg_b
                Let args_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with str_a, str_b
                If args_match is not equal to 1:
                    Return 0
                End If
                Set j to j plus 1
            End While
        End If

        Note: Let statements: compare the variable name.
        If kind_a is equal to HIR_LET_STATEMENT from HIR:
            Let var_a be proc let_var_name with stmt_a
            Let var_b be proc let_var_name with stmt_b
            Let vars_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with var_a, var_b
            If vars_match is not equal to 1:
                Return 0
            End If
        End If

        Note: If statements: compare the verbatim condition text.
        If kind_a is equal to HIR_IF_STATEMENT from HIR:
            Let cond_a be proc if_condition_text with stmt_a
            Let cond_b be proc if_condition_text with stmt_b
            Let conds_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with cond_a, cond_b
            If conds_match is not equal to 1:
                Return 0
            End If
        End If

        Note: For statements: compare the iterator variable name.
        If kind_a is equal to HIR_FOR_STATEMENT from HIR:
            Let iter_a be proc for_iterator_name with stmt_a
            Let iter_b be proc for_iterator_name with stmt_b
            Let iters_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with iter_a, iter_b
            If iters_match is not equal to 1:
                Return 0
            End If
        End If

        Note: Process definitions: compare the function name.
        If kind_a is equal to HIR_PROCESS_DEFINITION from HIR:
            Let proc_a be proc process_name with stmt_a
            Let proc_b be proc process_name with stmt_b
            Let procs_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with proc_a, proc_b
            If procs_match is not equal to 1:
                Return 0
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Probe entry point
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "main" returns Integer:
    Let results be proc create_test_results from TestUtils
    proc begin_suite from TestUtils with results, "CMake translation round-trip"

    Note:
    Representative CMakeLists.txt. Top-level statement order (0-indexed):
      0  cmake_minimum_required(VERSION 3.20)   -> call
      1  project(MyApp)                         -> call
      2  set(SRC_FILES main.c util.c)           -> let statement
      3  add_executable(myapp ${SRC_FILES})     -> call
      4  add_library(mylib STATIC lib.c)        -> call
      5  target_link_libraries(myapp mylib)     -> call
      6  if(WIN32) ... endif()                  -> if statement
      7  foreach(f ${SRC_FILES}) ... endforeach -> for statement
      8  function(my_func) ... endfunction()    -> process definition
    Newlines are explicit \n in the Runa string literal.
    :End Note
    Let source be "cmake_minimum_required(VERSION 3.20)\nproject(MyApp)\nset(SRC_FILES main.c util.c)\nadd_executable(myapp ${SRC_FILES})\nadd_library(mylib STATIC lib.c)\ntarget_link_libraries(myapp mylib)\nif(WIN32)\n  message(STATUS windows)\nendif()\nforeach(f ${SRC_FILES})\n  message(STATUS ${f})\nendforeach()\nfunction(my_func)\n  message(STATUS hello)\nendfunction()"

    Note: --- Stage 1: source -> HIR ---
    Let hir1 be proc cmake_source_to_hir with source
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "pipeline produced HIR program", hir1

    Let block1 be proc program_block with hir1
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "HIR program carries a statement block", block1

    Let stmt_count be proc block_count with block1
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "HIR block has 9 statements", stmt_count, 9

    Note: --- Stage 1 content: cmake_minimum_required command ---
    Let cmr_call be proc block_stmt_at with block1, 0
    Let cmr_name be proc call_name with cmr_call
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "stmt[0] is cmake_minimum_required", cmr_name, "cmake_minimum_required"

    Note: --- project command ---
    Let proj_call be proc block_stmt_at with block1, 1
    Let proj_name be proc call_name with proj_call
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "stmt[1] is project", proj_name, "project"
    Let proj_arg be proc arg_string with proc call_arg_at with proj_call, 0
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "project arg is 'MyApp'", proj_arg, "MyApp"

    Note: --- set() lowers to a let statement ---
    Let set_stmt be proc block_stmt_at with block1, 2
    Let set_kind be proc node_kind with set_stmt
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "stmt[2] is HIR let statement", set_kind, HIR_LET_STATEMENT from HIR
    Let set_var be proc let_var_name with set_stmt
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "set() variable is 'SRC_FILES'", set_var, "SRC_FILES"

    Note: --- add_executable command ---
    Let exe_call be proc block_stmt_at with block1, 3
    Let exe_name be proc call_name with exe_call
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "stmt[3] is add_executable", exe_name, "add_executable"
    Let exe_target be proc arg_string with proc call_arg_at with exe_call, 0
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "add_executable target is 'myapp'", exe_target, "myapp"

    Note: --- add_library command ---
    Let lib_call be proc block_stmt_at with block1, 4
    Let lib_name be proc call_name with lib_call
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "stmt[4] is add_library", lib_name, "add_library"
    Let lib_target be proc arg_string with proc call_arg_at with lib_call, 0
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "add_library target is 'mylib'", lib_target, "mylib"

    Note: --- target_link_libraries command ---
    Let tll_call be proc block_stmt_at with block1, 5
    Let tll_name be proc call_name with tll_call
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "stmt[5] is target_link_libraries", tll_name, "target_link_libraries"

    Note: --- if() lowers to an if statement ---
    Let if_stmt be proc block_stmt_at with block1, 6
    Let if_kind be proc node_kind with if_stmt
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "stmt[6] is HIR if statement", if_kind, HIR_IF_STATEMENT from HIR
    Let if_cond be proc if_condition_text with if_stmt
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "if condition text is 'WIN32'", if_cond, "WIN32"

    Note: --- foreach() lowers to a for statement ---
    Let for_stmt be proc block_stmt_at with block1, 7
    Let for_kind be proc node_kind with for_stmt
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "stmt[7] is HIR for statement", for_kind, HIR_FOR_STATEMENT from HIR
    Let for_iter be proc for_iterator_name with for_stmt
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "foreach iterator is 'f'", for_iter, "f"

    Note: --- function() lowers to a process definition ---
    Let func_stmt be proc block_stmt_at with block1, 8
    Let func_kind be proc node_kind with func_stmt
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "stmt[8] is HIR process definition", func_kind, HIR_PROCESS_DEFINITION from HIR
    Let func_name be proc process_name with func_stmt
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "function name is 'my_func'", func_name, "my_func"

    Note: --- Stage 2: HIR -> CMake text ---
    Let emitted be proc hir_to_cmake from CMakeBackend with hir1
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "backend produced CMake text", emitted

    Let emitted_len be proc string_length from StringCore with emitted
    proc assert_greater_than from TestUtils with results, "emitted CMake is non-empty", emitted_len, 0

    Note: --- Stage 3: re-parse the emitted CMake text -> HIR (the SECOND
    Note: emission), then assert the two statement streams are structurally
    Note: equal. This is the load-bearing round-trip assertion. ---
    Let hir2 be proc cmake_source_to_hir with emitted
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "re-parse of emitted CMake produced HIR", hir2

    Let block2 be proc program_block with hir2
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "re-parsed HIR carries a statement block", block2

    Let count2 be proc block_count with block2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "re-parsed block preserves 9 statements", count2, 9

    Note: Spot-check survival on the SECOND emission directly (not just stage 1).
    Let r_set be proc block_stmt_at with block2, 2
    Let r_set_var be proc let_var_name with r_set
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip set() variable survives", r_set_var, "SRC_FILES"

    Let r_if be proc block_stmt_at with block2, 6
    Let r_if_cond be proc if_condition_text with r_if
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip if condition survives", r_if_cond, "WIN32"

    Let r_for be proc block_stmt_at with block2, 7
    Let r_for_iter be proc for_iterator_name with r_for
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip foreach iterator survives", r_for_iter, "f"

    Let r_func be proc block_stmt_at with block2, 8
    Let r_func_name be proc process_name with r_func
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip function name survives", r_func_name, "my_func"

    Let structurally_equal be proc hir_blocks_equal with block1, block2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip HIR is structurally equal", structurally_equal, 1

    proc print_summary from TestUtils with results
    Let failed be proc get_failed from TestUtils with results
    proc destroy_test_results from TestUtils with results

    Return failed
End Process
